            <section id="why-winter-prep-matters">
              <h2>Why winter prep matters</h2>
              <p>
                The green lawn you want in spring is decided in late fall. Cool-season turf stores
                energy underground when soil temperatures drop. A balanced feeding and a light
                overseed now fuel root growth, crowd out winter weeds, and prevent thin, patchy
                spots when growth resumes.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section id="fertilization-blueprint">
              <h3>Our fertilization blueprint</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Timing:</strong> After the first frost but before soil freezes, so nutrients reach
                  roots without pushing excess top growth.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ratio:</strong> A cool-season blend with elevated potassium to strengthen roots and
                  improve cold tolerance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Coverage:</strong> Even, cross-direction passes with a calibrated spreader to avoid
                  stripes or burn spots.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Clean edges:</strong> We blow granules off drives and walkways to protect concrete
                  and pavers.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section id="overseeding-steps">
              <h3>Overseeding without the bare patches</h3>
              <p>
                Overseeding fills gaps before winter dormancy sets in. We dethatch or lightly rake to
                open the canopy, then broadcast premium seed matched to your sun exposure. Consistent
                moisture is key: light, frequent watering for the first 10 to 14 days, then taper to
                deeper, less frequent cycles to train roots downward.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Prep the surface: rake leaves, loosen thatch, and level small depressions.</li>
                <li>Seed at the right rate: thicker in high-wear areas, lighter where turf is dense.</li>
                <li>Topdress lightly: a dusting of compost helps seed-to-soil contact and moisture.</li>
                <li>Protect new seed: keep foot traffic off until germination sets.</li>
              </ol>
            </section>

            <section id="watering-and-soil">
              <h3>Watering and soil checks</h3>
              <p>
                Irrigation should stay on the schedule until the first hard freeze. We aim for about
                1 inch of water per week split into several light cycles after seeding. If soil is
                compacted, a quick core aeration ahead of fertilization opens pathways for nutrients
                and water.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section id="simple-schedule">
              <h3>Simple schedule to follow</h3>
              <ul class="list-unstyled">
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Late October: soil test and adjust pH if needed</li>
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Early November: core aeration plus overseed</li>
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Mid November: balanced fertilizer with higher potassium</li>
                <li><i class="fa fa-check text-success"></i> Through first freeze: light, frequent irrigation</li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section id="how-we-measure">
